# Data Dictionary — sciscinet_sample.parquet (Wu, Wang & Evans 2019)

Source: SciSciNet (Lin et al. 2023), 40,000-paper random sample.
Original paper analyzes >65M papers, patents, and software products spanning 1954–2014;
this sample is a stratified random subset for reproduction.

| column | type | description |
|---|---|---|
| paper_id | str | unique paper identifier (SciSciNet) |
| year | int | publication year |
| author_count | int | number of authors on the paper |
| institution_count | int | number of distinct institutions |
| reference_count | int | number of references (citations made) |
| citation_count | int | total citations received |
| citation_count_5y | int | citations received within 5 years |
| disruption_score | float | CD-disruption index in [-1, 1]; positive = disrupting, negative = consolidating |
| novelty_score | float | novelty indicator |
| conventionality_score | float | conventionality indicator |
| doc_type | str | document type (paper / patent / software) |

Key columns for Wu2019 reproduction: `author_count` (team size), `disruption_score` (the outcome).
The paper's central claim: smaller teams tend to *disrupt* (higher disruption_score), larger teams tend to *develop* (lower/consolidating disruption_score).
